entry.title: Reland "[dPWA] Show origin in web app title bar when navigating ..."
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit 9c83a3fdfaf3cabeb0f8d1b55ac543b54c26b7af



The original CL caused browser tests to fail even through there were no

changes that impacted those tests in an obvious way. See

crbug.com/1488734 for details. The failures could have been caused by

changes in animation delay and timing, which the reverted CL did modify.



Patch 8 fixes the test failures by replacing usages of RunUntilIdle with

a view visibility waiter to more reliably wait for the view in question

to become visible.

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4909892/7..8



Original change's description:

> [dPWA] Show origin in web app title bar when navigating across origins

>

> When navigating in a web app window between different origins that are

> within the app's extended scope (using scope_extensions), the user needs

> to be kept aware of their security context. As a CCT UI is no longer

> displayed when navigating within extended scope, this CL modifies the

> title bar origin text both in terms of what is shown and when it is

> shown.

>

> Previous behavior:

> - Always show origin of start URL.

> - Shows text when the app window launches or when theme color changes.

> - Does not show text when a CCT UI is also shown.

> - Except when theme color changes.

>

> New behavior (with feature flag enabled):

> - Shows origin of current committed web content instead of always

> showing origin of the app's start url.

> - Shows origin when navigating to a different origin.

> - Even when a CCT UI is shown.

>

entry.title: Improve backdrop filter calculations in SkiaRenderer
entry.content:
Pulls all of the bounds analysis for how to clip the output and input

of a backdrop filter into the CalculateRPDQParams function. Improves

the calculations for the `filter_bounds` value to be tighter for

backdrop filters since their output is always restricted.



Optimizes more cases to have backdrop output restricted by just a

clip instead of introducing an image filter node at the end. Switches

the input cropping node from a no-op Offset(0,0) to a proper `Crop`

that can define the boundary tilemode to apply (kClamp). This

actually fixes the behavior in the backdrop-offset unit test. It also

makes it possible to easily experiment with using mirror tiling for

content that is off screen.



Re-organizes some of the logic for clipping or clearing the backdrop

bounds into helper functions in RPDQParams so that

PrepareCanvasForRPDQ is more readable.



The backdrop logic to determine if an input crop is needed or not

used to have a bug (exposed when removing the staging flag

SK_USE_LEGACY_CONTENT_BOUNDS_PROPAGATION). The input bounds

calculation needs to use a null src rect so that the returned value

has no additional content restriction. If it *still* matches the

target output bounds, then we know it's not a pixel-moving backdrop

filter. I confirmed that the backdrop boundary layout tests work

correctly with and without the above staging flag.



Updates the conversion of FilterOperations to PaintFilter to define

the tiling geometry, so that clamp, mirror, and repeat explicitly

apply to the edges of a layer (instead of previously just the edge

of whatever image size happened to come through the pipeline). This

currently is only taken advantage of in SkiaRenderer,

SoftwareRenderer continues to use the legacy (less stable/defined)

tiling behavior.

entry.title: [ios] Fix for leading icon animation on omnibox focus
entry.content:
Previously the leading icon was shifted with the omnibox text as part

of the focus animation, so in addition to the scale-in it was also

moving. This is not what UX wanted. This change modifies the animation

to only shift the "text field" rather than the whole "edit view" (which

includes the leading icon). This allows the scale-in effect to start

sooner, which gives it more time to complete and makes it look more

smooth. And it more closely matches the UX spec.

entry.title: android: explicitly destroy the stencil framebuffer.
entry.content:
gl::GLContext holds offscreen surfaces now. However, they are not

destroyed until very end...until the context is actually destroyed.



It's OK in most of the cases, but it is not good in case of

the AwGLSurfaceExternalStencil that subclasses the AwGLSurface and that

creates stencil framebuffers that has to be destroyed on a correct

context.



Given that surface is also offscreen one (changed in

https://crrev.com/c/4942195), gl::GLContext holds it and it's not

guaranteed that particular context will be current. As a result, no

context/wrong context crash may happen.



To mitigate the issue, add a helper stencil framebuffer destruction

method that AwGLSurfaceExternalStencil implements, and which is called

when OutputSurfaceProviderWebView no longer needs the surface.

entry.title: gpu: add EnablePerContextGLTextureCache for OzoneImageBacking.
entry.content:
There can be multiple of raster tasks that produce skia representation

over and over again, which triggers creation/destruction of glTexture

and the underlying EGLImage.



The idea behind the EGLImage is that it's reused/updated almost every

single frame. Reconstruction of that is not efficient. For example,

on LaCros, it takes about 200-400us to construct an EGLImage, which

makes the gpu thread more busy with the raster tasks (there can be

multiple of those as LaCros needs to rasterize to EGLImages).



A EnablePerContextGLTextureCache will make OzoneImageBacking store

TextureHolders on a per context basis.



The feature is disabled by default and will be enabled in a next

CL to ensure a smooth transition.



Test: OzoneImageBackingFactoryTest.UsesCacheForTextureHolders

entry.title: Adding experimental per vsync scroll jank metrics
entry.content:
Current scroll jank metrics are emitted per frame, this CL adds a

new variant of those metrics that is emitted per vsync since this

is the way Android jank is tracked.



For example a single frame that has 5 missed vsyncs will now have

5/64 missed frame in a window of 64 vsyncs, since the window now

represents vsyncs not frames, in the past this would have been

1/64, since only 1 frame was janky in a window of 64 frames.



This should make the metric more stable as the 99th percentile now

will represent hangs just like Android.



* Event.ScrollJank.MissedVsyncsPercentage.FixedWindow

Tracks missed vsync percentage

* Event.ScrollJank.MissedVsyncsSum.FixedWindow2

Tracks missed vsync sum in a **Vsync window** not a **frame window**

entry.title: Record www-subdomain conflicts during Url filtering
entry.content:
Adds a new histogram to record which Url conflicts differ

only on the trivial www subdomain inclusion during url

filtering.



The conflicts are captured with a new enum type which

distinguishes between: 1) conflicts that happen only

because of trivial subdomain differences (and would go

away completely if we strip the trivial subdomain),

2) conflicts that happen due to both trivial subdomain

differences and other matching conflicting entries

(these conflicts will no go away if we strip trivial

subdomains) and 3) conflicts that do not occur due to

trivial subdomains (and will remain unchanged if we

do trivial subdomain stripping).

entry.title: Reland "WebGPUSwapBufferProvider: Don't create SI with unsupported size."
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit 8994884a345c2466c89261fe1433b474558794b5



What's changed:

- Wrap deviceGetLimits call in CHECK() instead of DCHECK(). DCHECK(expr)

won't evaluate expr if dcheck is disabled. Thus deviceGetLimits was

optimized out when dcheck is off.



Original change's description:

> WebGPUSwapBufferProvider: Don't create SI with unsupported size.

>

> Currently WebGPUSwapBufferProvider::GetNewTexture() always tries

> to create a new shared image even if the size is larger than Dawn's

> maxTextureDimension2D limit. If the hardware cannot create a shared

> image with this size, Chrome will disconnect the GPU channel.

>

> We should skip the shared image creation if the size is larger than

> Dawn's maxTextureDimension2D limit. Because even if the shared image is

> successfully created, a WGPUTexture won't be able to be created from it

> anyway.

>

> This will fix the WebGPU CTS validation tests using getCurrentTexture

> on "overlimit" canvas when Graphite is enabled. Because with Graphite,

> a shared image larger than Dawn's maxTextureDimension2D limit is not

> allowed.

entry.title: Deprecate vector<v8::Local>, part 5
entry.content:
According to V8's public API documentation, local handles (i.e.,

objects of type v8::Local) "should never be allocated on the heap".

This disallows heap-allocated data structures containing instances of

v8::Local, like std::vector>. It is unfortunate

that the V8 API itself requires the usage of such data structures.



This CL continues the deprecation of such data structures. It replaces

such vectors with on-stack arrays of locals.



Most of the changes in this CL are trivial and are related to

chromecast/renderer.

entry.title: Remove GenericAutofillChange
entry.content:
GenericAutofillChange is the base class for AutocompleteChange and

AutofillDataModelChange (i.e. AutofillProfileChange, CreditCardChange,

etc.). It defines:

- The enum of changes types and a corresponding member variable.

- A member variable for the change key - an identifier used to identify

the autocomplete entry or the profile, card, etc.



This CL removes GenericAutofillChange and inlines it into the two

derived classes, AutocompleteChange and AutofillDataModelChange. This

allows redefining the change types in both classes and removing

EXPIRED changes for AutofillDataModelChange. Currently, only

AutocompleteChange uses them.



It also unblocks the path for removing redundancy in

AutofillDataModelChange: Currently, it has a member for the change key

and an additional member for the data_model. This is redundant, since

the key can generally be derived from the data model (e.g. given an

AutofillProfile, its GUID can be queried).

Moreover, it unblocks the path for the data_model optional for REMOVE modifications, by having something like a variant (e.g.

if a profile is supposed to be removed by GUID, the change shouldn't

need to contain the profile that's about to be deleted. Neither Sync nor

the PDM code cares about this information).



Lastly, it's nice to remove one layer of inheritance.



Note that the change type is kept an enum. Changing it to an enum class

should be done, but is beyond the scope of this CL.

entry.title: PlzDedicatedWorker: fix possible nullptr assignment.
entry.content:
As far as I took a look at the code, I suppose there can be nullptr

returned by `WorkerDevToolsManager::GetDevToolsHostFromToken`.

However, the callee looks using the returned value without ensuring

non-nullptr. I suppose it can cause the crash in crbug.com/1265325.



As far as I checked where the token comes, it looks coming from

`DedicatedWorker::ContinueStart`. At a glance, I misunderstood

that it can be newly created in `DevToolsAgent::WorkerThreadCreated`,

which happens only for Worklet, and not for DedicatedWorker.

Since `DedicatedWorker::Start` should record the `DedicatedWorkerHost`

`WorkerDevToolsManager::GetDevToolsHostFromToken` should be able to

find it.



The exceptional case is a `DedicatedWorkerHost` destruction.

If the destruction happens while `ChildTargetCreated` is inflight,

`WorkerDevToolsManager::GetDevToolsHostFromToken` may return nullptr.

I believe we can ignore it in that case because it is not possible

entry.title: [autopip] Use Blink's activation lifespan directly instead of copying
entry.content:
Currently, we have a constant in AutoPictureInPictureTabHelper of 5

seconds to represent the length of a user gesture. While a user gesture

is generally 5 seconds, on address-sanitizer builds, it's changed to 60

seconds to accommodate how slow those binaries are. Since the

AutoPictureInPictureTabHelper was always using 5 seconds, some of its

tests are flaky on address-sanitizer builds. To fix this, this CL

changes the AutoPictureInPictureTabHelper to directly use the constant

from Blink instead of its own, and therefore gets the longer 60-second

timer on address-sanitizer builds.
